<p>As you can see above there are two things which are visible only in the postâ€™s markdown version. You wonâ€™t see them here because they got processed by Jekyll and â€˜thrown outâ€™ while generating html version of this post.</p>

<p><code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">{: .lead}</code> inserted on a new line after a paragraphtells Jekyllâ€™s markdown processor (dactl uses <a href="https://kramdown.gettalong.org/">kramdown</a>) to add class <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">.lead</code> to the above <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">&lt;p&gt;</code> tag which results in a leading paragraph.</p>

<p><code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">&lt;!--break--&gt;</code>, inserted on a new line after <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">{: .lead}</code>, tells Jekyll that it should <a href="https://media.giphy.com/media/l46CxpYSFoFtN11ug/giphy.gif">â€˜breakâ€™</a> the post content at this point, so everything above it will become a post excerpt.</p>

<p class="notice-alert">The order is important here - <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">&lt;!--break--&gt;</code> comes <strong>after</strong> <code class="language-plaintext highlighter-rouge">{: .lead}</code> and because of that the leading paragraph/ post excerpt has itâ€™s font enlarged both on blog and post pages.</p>
